<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED1DFF9FFF54FD39FCABFD59" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B534515BED1DFF9FFF54FD39FCABFD59" blockId="15.[151,1437,259,970]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFF54FD39FECCFD01" bold="true" box="[199,334,655,681]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is from “Denji”, the main protagonist of 
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFB93FD39FB28FD01" box="[1024,1194,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Chainsaw Man</emphasis>
(a manga series written and illustrated by Fujimoto Tatsuki), who has chainsaws on arms after transformation, referring to the small sawtooth-like denticles on the embolus of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FD9102D0ED1DFF9FFF54FD4DFE1FFC61" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B534515BED1DFF9FFF54FD4DFE1FFC61" blockId="15.[151,1437,259,970]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFF54FD4DFEC0FCBD" bold="true" box="[199,322,763,789]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males can be easily distinguished from all congeners by the presence of small sawtooth-like denticles on embolus (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED1DFF9FFEFEFCA9FE73FC91" box="[365,497,799,825]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 84–86" captionStart-1="FIGURES 87–89" captionStartId-0="16.[151,264,1033,1057]" captionStartId-1="17.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox-0="[162,1430,181,1003]" captionTargetBox-1="[199,1400,190,1904]" captionTargetId-0="figure-19@16.[151,1436,181,1009]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@17.[181,1406,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId-0="16" captionTargetPageId-1="17" captionText-0="FIGURES 84–86. Palp of Charippus denjii Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., holotype, in prolateral (84), ventral (85) and retrolateral (86) view." captionText-1="FIGURES 87–89. Palp of Charippus denjii Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., holotype, in ventral (87), retrolateral (88) and dorsal (89) view." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500793" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500795" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6500793/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6500795/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Figs 84–88</figureCitation>
). Markings and body form of the new species are similar to 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED1DFF9FFB0EFC96FAB1FC91" authority="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang, 2022" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[1181,1331,799,826]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heishiding" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFB0EFC96FAB1FC91" box="[1181,1331,799,826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">C. heishiding</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFAA8FCA9FA17FC91" bold="true" box="[1339,1429,799,825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED1DFF9FFAA8FCA9FA17FC91" box="[1339,1429,799,825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but can be distinguished by the distally bifurcated RTA and the copulatory ducts swerving for six times (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED1DFF9FFAACFCF5FF62FC29" captionStart="FIGURES 90–94" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1687,1711]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,182,1644]" captionTargetId="figure-19@18.[151,1436,181,1663]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 90–94. Female genitalia of Charippus denjii Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov.. 90, 92. Ventral view; 91, 93. Dorsal view; 94. CD path." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500797/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Figs 91, 93–94</figureCitation>
; vs. the RTA is not bifurcated distally and the copulatory ducts swerving for 10 times in 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED1DFF9FFB48FCDEFAF0FC29" authority="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang, 2022" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[1243,1394,871,898]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heishiding" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFB48FCDEFAF0FC29" box="[1243,1394,871,898]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">C. heishiding</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFAE8FCD1FF4AFC0D" bold="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED1DFF9FFAE8FCD1FF4AFC0D" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). It also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="728B2AD8ED1DFF9FFE2FFC3AFDD1FC0D" authority="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang, 2022" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang &amp; Maddison &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2022" box="[444,595,907,934]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Charippus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heishiding" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFE2FFC3AFDD1FC0D" box="[444,595,907,934]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">C. heishiding</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="87FF8D49ED1DFF9FFDC9FC3DFD36FC0D" bold="true" box="[602,692,907,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9CCC3032ED1DFF9FFDC9FC3DFD36FC0D" box="[602,692,907,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the presence of a slightly sclerotized area on the ventral abdomen in males (
<figureCitation id="2DB04DDEED1DFF9FFEAFFC19FE12FC61" box="[316,400,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,993,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-337@15.[151,1436,993,1871]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Charippus denjii Yu, Maddison &amp; Zhang, sp. nov., male (77, 79–80, 82) and female (78, 81, 83). 77–79. Habitus, in dorsal (77–78) and ventral (79) view; 80–81. Front view of carapace; 82–83. Details of chelicera, apical (82) and back view (83), arrows pointing to triangular projections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500790" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500790/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="E1F401D3ED1DFF9FFF04F8D0FD5FF86F" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500790" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6500790" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500790/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="166" startId="15.[151,264,1894,1918]" targetBox="[151,1436,993,1871]" targetPageId="15">
